Anthem Prep (6th-12th grades) has a small number of seats open which gives interested families an opportunity to join us now, during a time when the transition will be easier and school choice is more important that ever!

For the rest of 1st Quarter, recommend a family to Anthem Prep and, once they enroll, you’ll get a Consumables Voucher for each student that enrolled! A Consumable Voucher can be redeemed for one, complete set of consumables for any grade level (including readers, music, and art). If you’ve already purchased your consumables this year, save the vouchers for next year! Tag your friends and family that might be interested in learning more about Anthem Prep.

post_text:
Welcome Mr. Ammerman to Anthem Prep!

I have a Master's degree in Natural Science from ASU and have taught K-12 all grades and all subjects as well as collegiately in physics and chemistry since 2011. Prior to teaching I was in the US Navy as a Missile Technician launching ballistic nuclear missiles on submarines. My career dreams from childhood to today in roughly chronological order were astronaut, helicopter pilot, rocket scientist, Arch Villain, Philosophy teacher, Public Debater, and finally Physics/Chemistry Instructor. The picture is when my wife and I went skydiving.

post_text:
Welcome Mr. Blaauw to Anthem Prep!

Cameron Blaauw is a native of Southern Ontario and also grew up in South Holland, Illinois. He developed a passion for languages and literature while studying at Hillsdale College. In 2010, he graduated with a BA in Spanish from Hillsdale and went on to further his studies with the goal of working in education. At New Saint Andrews College in Moscow, Idaho he earned an M. St. in Classical Christian Studies with an emphasis on classical languages. While finishing this degree he taught Latin at Logos School. Afterwards he received an MA in Classics at the University of Kentucky. Following this, Mr. Blaauw accepted a position to teach Latin at Veritas Preparatory Academy in Phoenix, Arizona where he has taught for the past five years. He is delighted to join Anthem Preparatory Academy and further the mission of shaping the minds and hearts of young men and women.

post_text:
Please welcome Mrs. Hinthorn to Anthem Prep!

Elise Hinthorn is excited to begin her first year of teaching at Anthem Prep as the 8th and 9th grade Latin teacher. This summer she moved with her husband and stepdaughter from Alabama, to be closer to his family. Mrs. Hinthorn received her BA in Classics from Samford University in Birmingham, Alabama. While at Samford she began teaching Latin 1 for a local homeschool cooperative, where she fell in love with teaching. After graduation, she taught 6th-8th Latin at a local public school for 1 year and then moved to a Classical Christian School in Birmingham where for 10 years she taught Latin, Greek, Drama, Literature, Yearbook, Photography, and Bible. Outside of the classroom Mrs. Hinthorn enjoys traveling, hiking, photography, painting, theatre, and spending time with friends and family.

post_text:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT
🦅Emily Linden🦅
I’m most grateful for my growth personally and individually in understanding ‒ about reality, human nature, the good, etc.‒ which ultimately gives me meaning and fulfillment. Similarly, what impacted me most academically were the philosophical discussions in which I took part mainly during Humane Letters seminars but also after class and among some close friends during my free time. Though I also enjoyed many of the other courses, especially all of the math classes, the questions we encounter in the books we read in Humane Letters are some of, if not the most, urgent and pressing questions that any person should answer. During my time at Anthem Prep, I’ve been able to find some answers to those questions, but most importantly, I’ve developed a determination ‒ a conviction ‒ to find the rest. I will be attending Arizona State University majoring in Physics with a minor in Philosophy or World Religion. My goal in life is to find meaning by pursuing and getting to the truth at the most basic level.

Anthem Prep has taught me how to think critically, work in a group Anthem Prep has impacted my life in such an amazing way. It has given me the desire to learn and be excited about it. Anthem Prep has also given me my best friends, who I know will be my life-long friends. I am extremely grateful to have been able to go to such an amazing school. My favorite classes are Humane Letters and Calculus II. They are both really fun because they allow you to solve a problem as a class and understand the reasoning behind the solution. Chloe will be attending Northern Arizona University to study nursing to become a Pediatric Oncology Nurse.

Anthem Prep has taught me how to think critically, work in a group setting, and constructively and creatively solve problems. Anthem Prep has also allowed me to have a close, tight-knit group of friends as well as equip me with a solid work ethic and the understanding that failure and restarting is fundamental to learning. After high school, I will be attending Arizona State University, where I will be studying Architectural Studies at the Herberger Institute for Design and the Arts and obtain my Bachelor of Science in Design. I plan on going back to school and graduate with a Master's of Architecture and become a licensed Architect.

Great Hearts Academies plans to extend spring break at all of our campuses through the week of March 16th. There will be no regular school or after-school activities during this week. We plan to resume classes on March 23, 2020. You can stay informed on our website: https://www.greatheartsamerica.org/coronavirus/

We are very sorry for the inconveniences and hardships this may cause, but we sincerely believe it is in the best interest of our community at this time.

post_text:
From Mr. Goodrich-
We spent most of the day traveling yesterday but were able to spend the evening visiting the monuments. It is so wonderful to see the awe, gratitude, and reverence our students have in times like these. At the Lincoln Memorial, a group of students took turns spontaneously reciting the Gettysburg Address and the beginning of MLK's "I Have a Dream" speech. After his recitation, one student said, "That just felt right." The types of questions they are asking, the references to history they were making, and the general wonder and thoughtfulness they show toward our heritage are inspiring and show that this education they are about to complete has been one giant leap toward being virtuous and thoughtful humans and citizens. @ Washington D.C.

post_text: Our 11th grade Physics students are attempting to maintain a raw egg’s shell during a drop from varying heights. This is done by reducing the amount of force exerted on the egg by increasing the amount of time it takes to stop the egg from falling. This science is similar to how airbags work in vehicular accidents. *more pictures and videos in the comments*

A Note from the Office Manager: Shefali Kubavat
Great Hearts lead office sent an email to parents with a link to access the re-enrollment portal to re-enroll their current Anthem Prep students for school year 2020-2021. Below are the instructions on next steps:
• Review all pages on the portal and make any changes if necessary.
• Print out the re-enrollment papers at the end.
• Sign all required signature boxes.
• Make a copy of your proof of residency.
• Drop off paperwork during one of the assigned dates below
o 3/24/20 – 4:00 – 6:00 pm, Commons
o 3/25/20 – 2:00 – 4:30 pm, Flag Pole
o 3/26/20 – 4:00 – 6:00 pm, Commons
Please do not send paperwork with your student to school. Paperwork will not be accepted by the front office staff.

post_text:
Before break, our 2nd grade students enjoyed a lesson on machines. Thank you to the Schwitters family for your time.
What is work? How much force do I need to move an object? Is there something I can use to help make work easier? These are the questions our second graders were asking as they studied a unit about simple machines. Pulleys, levers, wedges and inclined planes were described and documented as we learned how simple and compound machines help us in our daily lives. This year, our unit culminated with a visit from Mr. Schwitters. Mr. Schwitters, an engineer at EC Source Services and a parent of a second grader, came to talk about how machines help him in his daily work. Our classes were able to experiment with marshmallow catapults to discover if a longer lever would add distance to our launches. A fun time was had by all and our teams always appreciate the help of our esteemed parents.

After watching the local radar and keeping your and your student’s safety in mind, please note the following early dismissal for today:

Kindergarten through 2nd grade: Dismissal will be at 2:30 PM
Grades 3 – 12: Dismissal will be at 2:45 PM

Kindergarten through 2nd grade students who cannot be picked up at the early dismissal time will be in their classroom; please come to the front door of the 200-building (near the parking lot) to pick up your student.

3rd – 5th grade students who cannot be picked up at the early dismissal time will be in their classroom; please come to the front door of the main building (the two-story building) to pick up your student.

MS and HS students who cannot be picked up at the early dismissal time will be in the gymnasium; please come to the gym to pick up your student.

All students must be picked up by 4:00 PM.

Homework club is cancelled for today.

Thank you!

post_text: 54 tenth graders signed up for an optional lab this Saturday morning, coming into school at 7:30am to do a Titration Lab with a few of their favorite teachers: Ms. Armer, Mr. Curry, and Mrs. Mickley! Students were willing to come in on the weekend because this is an AWESOME lab! They are using a strong base (sodium hydroxide) to neutralize a weak acid (acetic acid). They're hoping to get a perfectly pink solution, which indicates that they have found the equivalence point. (Session 1 pics on Instagram) #weloveourteachers

post_text:
Please join us at Anthem Preparatory Academy tonight at 6:30 pm to hear firsthand from the president of Great Hearts Arizona, Erik Twist, about the nature and necessity of charter school education. You will be given an opportunity to learn about the distinction between charter and public education, the nature of charter school funding, and the uniqueness of Great Hearts Academies. There will be an opportunity to bring any questions you have regarding charter schools and Great Hearts Academies.

If you are unable to join us tonight, we would like to extend to you an opportunity to have coffee with the Headmaster of Anthem Prep, Grant Goodrich. Families new to or curious about Anthem Prep are invited to join him at Amped Coffee Company on Monday, May 6th from 8 to 9:30 am. There will be an additional time to meet in the evening on Monday, May 13th at 5 to 6:30 pm. Families are encouraged to bring questions they have regarding the school or simply to drop by to get to know our school’s headmaster. No need to RVSP.
We hope to see you there!

With only one week left, we are in the home stretch of our Tax Credit drive. We still need 40 Tax Credits to reach our goal.

It’s important.

Did you know:
• It takes 2 Tax Credits to support our Archway drama and art clubs?
• It takes 2 Tax Credits to bring our Archway outreach programs to our campus?
• It takes 3 Tax Credits to rent one bus for one away athletic game?
• It takes 5 Tax Credits to pay each coach?
• It takes 13 Tax Credits to outfit each team in uniforms?
• It takes 39 Tax Credits to rent a field or gym for athletics?

Participation fees cover about 50% of what we truly need to operate a healthy athletics and extra-curricular program. The rest is covered by Tax Credit funds.

Please contribute your Tax Credit today! https://anthemprep.configio.com/moneyrequest?id=2

Thank you,

Teresa Clark and Grant Goodrich

post_text: Congratulations to Nick Yarema, this year’s Archway Bard! After competing in round one against 35 students in grades 3-5, Nick earned his way to round two, where he competed among the top 12 participants. He won the top spot with his delivery of William Shakespeare’s, St. Crispin’s Day speech from the play Henry V. We wish Nick good luck as he advances to the Great Hearts Bard Competition in April.

Good morning, Eagles! Don't forget! It's FIELD DAY! Please see the following for drop off and pick up:

Campus for all K-5th Graders: 8-11:45 AM (K-2), 12:00 pm (3-5). Students will report to his/her classroom after 7:30 am.

Anthem Community Park for all 6th-12th grade students: 8-12pm (Drop off by 7:40 near sand volleyball courts.)

Please bring water, hat, sunscreen if desired. The school will provide a bottle of water and a granola bar.

Good afternoon!

I am reaching out with a friendly reminder that contributions to the Arizona Public School Tax Credit are due by April 15, 2019.

Don't forget our Tax Credit contest! The Archway class with the highest amount of participation will receive a Pizza and Otter Pop Party on May 3. The Prep House with the highest tax credit participation will receive a visit from a Phoenix S.W.A.T and K-9 unit and a lunch on the field on May 3.

Remember, you will receive your contribution back as a dollar-for-dollar credit on your state taxes AND our students will be able to participate in the extra-curricular and outreach programs they deserve!

Please feel free to contact me should you have any questions. Go Eagles! Diane Tyson 623.223.1588

https://anthemprep.configio.com/moneyrequest?id=2
